article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw scored 16 of her 20 points in the first half and the Washington Mystics beat Houston 70-64 Thursday night, snapping an eight-game losing streak to the Comets.
article.headline: In ninth meeting, Mystics finally beat Comets
article.linkText: Holdsclaw shoots Mystics to first win over Comets
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw scored 16 of her 20 points in the first half and the Washington Mystics beat Houston 70-64 Thursday night, snapping an eight-game losing streak to the Comets.

Holdsclaw hit a jumper to start the second half, but then went scoreless until her jumper with 11.2 seconds left made it 70-64. Holdsclaw, who leads the WNBA in scoring and rebounding, grabbed 10 rebounds for the Mystics (5-1), who are off to their best start ever.

After Houston pulled to 62-59, Washington's Vicky Bullett
sandwiched two 3-pointers around one by Kelley Gibson of the Comets
for a 68-62 lead with 1:36 left.

"We thought we would come back, and we would come back, and we would get there,'' Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "But we could never get over the hump.''

Holdsclaw called the early season win a big one.

"The difference is that we have a coach who has implemented a
game plan that utilizes our versatility,'' Holdsclaw said. "It's
still early, but it was a gut-check game.''

Tina Thompson led Houston (5-3) with 18 points, while Sheryl
Swoopes was held to 10 on 5-for-18 shooting from the field. Swoopes
missed all four of her free throws.

"Tina didn't have an easy shot all night, and Swoopes
definitely didn't,'' Washington coach Marianne Stanley said. "I
have players that have listened really well. There haven't been too
many surprises.''

Holdsclaw had seven points in a 13-2 run that gave Washington a
13-4 lead. She had layup, a three-point play and two free throws in
the run. The closest the Comets got in the first half was 34-31.

The Mystics went up 45-35 on a jumper by Asia Jones with 16:08
to play. Tina Thompson then scored 10 straight points for the
Comets as they got within 49-47 with 10:57 to play.

   Annie Burgess and Helen Luz hit 3-pointers to increase the lead
to 55-47.

"We got plenty of shots. We didn't make enough of them,''
Chancellor said.

Stacy Dales-Schuman had 11 points for Washington and Bullett had 10.
